---
import DemoPageLayout from '../../layouts/DemoPageLayout.astro';
import FourierTransformDemo from '../../components/demos/FourierTransformDemo';
import KatexEq from '../../components/ui/KatexEq';
---

<DemoPageLayout
  title="Fourier Transform Demo"
  domain="signal-processing"
  difficulty="beginner"
  description="Explore the DFT: build a signal from sinusoids and see its spectrum. Visualize windowing, aliasing, and spectral leakage."
>
  <div slot="intro">
    <p>
      The Discrete Fourier Transform (DFT) decomposes a finite-length time-domain signal into
      its frequency components. It is the mathematical foundation of virtually every signal
      processing system &mdash; from audio codecs to radar receivers.
    </p>
    <p>
      This demo lets you compose a signal from up to three sinusoidal components and observe
      the resulting spectrum. Apply a window function to see how spectral leakage is reduced.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div slot="equations">
    <KatexEq display={true} client:only="react">
      {"X[k] = \\sum_{n=0}^{N-1} x[n]\\, e^{-j 2\\pi kn / N}"}
    </KatexEq>
    <KatexEq display={true} client:only="react">
      {"x[n] = \\sum_{i} A_i \\sin\\!\\left(2\\pi f_i n / f_s\\right)"}
    </KatexEq>
  </div>

  <FourierTransformDemo client:only="react" />

  <div slot="interpretation">
    <p>
      Each sinusoidal component appears as a peak at its frequency. When the signal frequency is not
      an exact integer multiple of &Delta;f = f&#8337;/N, energy spreads into neighboring bins &mdash;
      this is <strong>spectral leakage</strong>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Applying a window (Hann, Hamming, Blackman) tapers the signal edges to zero, reducing leakage
      at the cost of slightly wider peaks (lower frequency resolution).
    </p>
  </div>
</DemoPageLayout>
